<section xml:id="S_gcd">
  <title>The Greatest Common Divisor</title>
  
    <worksheet margin="1in" xml:id="PA_gcd">
      <title>Beginning Activity 1: The Greatest Common Divisor</title>
      
      <exercise>
        <statement>
          <p>
            Explain what it means to say that a nonzero integer <m>m</m> divides an integer <m>n</m>.
            Recall that we use the notation
            <m>m \mid n</m> to indicate that the nonzero integer <m>m</m> divides the integer <m>n</m>.
          </p>
        </statement>
      </exercise>
      <exercise>
        <statement>
          <p>
            Let <m>m</m> and <m>n</m> be integers with <m>m \ne 0</m>.
            Explain what it means to say that <m>m</m> does not divide <m>n</m>.
          </p>
        </statement>
      </exercise>

      <assemblage xml:id="gcd">
        <title>Definition</title>
        <idx><h>common divisor</h></idx>
        <idx><h>greatest common divisor</h></idx>
        <notation>
          <usage><m>\gcd ( {a, b} )</m></usage>
          <description>greatest common divisor of <m>a</m> and <m>b</m></description>
        </notation>
          <p>
            Let <m>a</m> and <m>b</m> be integers, not both 0.
            A <term>common divisor</term>
                
            of <m>a</m> and <m>b</m> is any nonzero integer that divides both <m>a</m> and <m>b</m>.
            The <term>largest</term> natural number that divides both <m>a</m> and <m>b</m> is called the
            <term>greatest common divisor</term>
                
            of <m>a</m> and <m>b</m>.
            The greatest common divisor of <m>a</m> and <m>b</m> is denoted by 
            <m>\gcd \left( {a, b} \right)</m>.
          </p>
        
      </assemblage>

      <exercise xml:id="PA_gcd1">
        <statement>
          <p>
            Use the roster method to list the elements of the set that contains all the natural 
            numbers that are divisors of 48.
          </p>
        </statement>
      </exercise>
      <exercise xml:id="PA_gcd2">
        <statement>
          <p>
            Use the roster method to list the elements of the set that contains all the natural 
            numbers that are divisors of 84.
          </p>
        </statement>
      </exercise>
